Lab Activity
Prompt 1: Load and Visualize Data

Load the global_economy dataset from the tsibble package.
Plot GDP for a specific country (e.g., “United States”). Assess stationarity visually.

Solution:

library(tsibbledata)
data("global_economy")

# Plot GDP for the United States
global_economy |&gt;
  filter(Country == "United States") |&gt;
  autoplot(GDP) +
  labs(title = "US GDP (Non-Stationary)", y = "GDP")







Prompt 2: Test for Stationarity

Use the KPSS test to check for stationarity.
Determine the required differencing order using unitroot_ndiffs.

Solution:

# KPSS test
global_economy |&gt;
  filter(Country == "United States") |&gt;
  features(GDP, unitroot_kpss)

# A tibble: 1 × 3
  Country       kpss_stat kpss_pvalue
  &lt;fct&gt;             &lt;dbl&gt;       &lt;dbl&gt;
1 United States      1.49        0.01

# Differencing order
global_economy |&gt;
  filter(Country == "United States") |&gt;
  features(GDP, unitroot_ndiffs)

# A tibble: 1 × 2
  Country       ndiffs
  &lt;fct&gt;          &lt;int&gt;
1 United States      2


–&gt;
Prompt 3: Apply Transformations

Apply first differencing to the GDP series.
Apply a Box-Cox transformation using Guerrero’s method to estimate λ.
Re-test stationarity using the KPSS test.

Solution:

# First difference
us_gdp_diff &lt;- global_economy |&gt;
  filter(Country == "United States") |&gt;
  mutate(DiffGDP = difference(GDP))

# Box-Cox transformation
lambda &lt;- global_economy |&gt;
  filter(Country == "United States") |&gt;
  features(GDP, features = guerrero) |&gt;
  pull(lambda_guerrero)

us_gdp_boxcox &lt;- global_economy |&gt;
  filter(Country == "United States") |&gt;
  mutate(BoxCoxGDP = box_cox(GDP, lambda))

# Re-test stationarity
us_gdp_boxcox |&gt;
  features(BoxCoxGDP, unitroot_kpss)

# A tibble: 1 × 3
  Country       kpss_stat kpss_pvalue
  &lt;fct&gt;             &lt;dbl&gt;       &lt;dbl&gt;
1 United States      1.55        0.01
